1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:08,808
Here's a reflection on a familiar phrase we rarely examine closely: the essay "Life is Short" by Paul Graham, written in January 2016.

2
00:00:08,808 --> 00:00:11,529
Graham begins with a childhood question.

3
00:00:11,529 --> 00:00:16,904
Is life actually short, or are we just complaining about the fact that it ends?

4
00:00:16,904 --> 00:00:19,557
For years he had no way to answer this.

5
00:00:19,557 --> 00:00:24,456
Then he had children, and the answer became clear: life really is short.

6
00:00:24,456 --> 00:00:30,536
What changed his mind was learning to convert time, a continuous quantity, into discrete units.

7
00:00:30,536 --> 00:00:34,056
You only get fifty-two weekends with your two-year-old.

8
00:00:34,056 --> 00:00:41,160
If the magic of Christmas lasts from ages three to ten, you'll watch your child experience it just eight times.

9
00:00:41,160 --> 00:00:44,104
And eight, he notes, is not a lot of anything.

10
00:00:44,104 --> 00:00:48,456
Like a handful of eight peanuts, the quantity feels plainly limited.

11
00:00:48,456 --> 00:00:53,230
So life is short. Does knowing this matter? For Graham, it does.

12
00:00:53,230 --> 00:00:59,495
It gives real force to the phrase "life is too short for that." If you find yourself

13
00:00:59,495 --> 00:01:03,672
thinking it, you should try to eliminate whatever it is.

14
00:01:03,672 --> 00:01:05,442
What is life too short for?

15
00:01:05,442 --> 00:01:10,227
The word that comes to his mind is bullshit, the junk food of experience.

16
00:01:10,227 --> 00:01:15,863
He means unnecessary meetings, pointless disputes, bureaucracy, posturing, cleaning up

17
00:01:15,863 --> 00:01:20,976
other people's mistakes, traffic jams, and addictive but unrewarding pastimes.

18
00:01:20,976 --> 00:01:23,447
This junk enters your life in two ways.

19
00:01:23,447 --> 00:01:28,262
Some is forced on you by circumstance, since making money is mostly errands.

20
00:01:28,262 --> 00:01:33,838
But you can reduce even that by prioritizing bullshit-avoidance over money and prestige,

21
00:01:33,838 --> 00:01:38,463
choosing better employers, or, as a freelancer, dropping toxic customers.

22
00:01:38,463 --> 00:01:45,686
The other kind sneaks in by tricking you, and that's harder to remove, because it has to be good at deceiving you.

23
00:01:45,686 --> 00:01:47,587
His example is arguing online.

24
00:01:47,587 --> 00:01:53,542
When someone attacks you, your instinct is to defend yourself, but it's usually better not to.

25
00:01:53,542 --> 00:01:57,597
Otherwise, he says, those people are literally taking your life.

26
00:01:57,597 --> 00:02:06,024
And as technology advances, the things we enjoy grow more addictive, so we must consciously ask: is this how I want to spend my time?

27
00:02:06,024 --> 00:02:09,846
Beyond avoiding waste, we should actively seek what matters.

28
00:02:09,846 --> 00:02:13,413
Most people only gradually learn to tell the difference.

29
00:02:13,413 --> 00:02:22,012
For the young, much confusion comes from artificial situations, worrying what other kids think, which nearly every adult later regrets.

30
00:02:22,012 --> 00:02:26,917
One useful test: ask whether you'll still care about something in the future.

31
00:02:26,917 --> 00:02:31,949
Fake importance has a sharp peak that jabs at you but little substance beneath.

32
00:02:31,949 --> 00:02:37,300
Meanwhile, having coffee with a friend genuinely matters. Small children matter too.

33
00:02:37,300 --> 00:02:43,224
When they tug your sleeve and ask you to play, that's usually the bullshit-minimizing choice.

34
00:02:43,224 --> 00:02:46,491
Because life is short, its shortness surprises us.

35
00:02:46,491 --> 00:02:52,306
We take things for granted, then they're gone. The saddest windows close when people die.

36
00:02:52,306 --> 00:02:56,879
After his mother's death, Graham wished he'd spent more time with her.

37
00:02:56,879 --> 00:03:04,066
His answer isn't to dwell morbidly on death, but to cultivate impatience about the things you most want to do.

38
00:03:04,066 --> 00:03:09,816
Don't wait to climb the mountain, write the book, or visit your mother. Just don't wait.

39
00:03:09,816 --> 00:03:15,326
When you don't have much of something, you can try to get more and savor what you have.

40
00:03:15,326 --> 00:03:21,596
How you live affects how long you live, but paying closer attention to your time matters even more.

41
00:03:21,596 --> 00:03:23,370
It is possible to slow time.

42
00:03:23,370 --> 00:03:27,360
Children help, filling life with moments too perfect to ignore.

43
00:03:27,360 --> 00:03:32,560
His closing advice is simple and clear: relentlessly prune bullshit, don't wait to do the

44
00:03:32,560 --> 00:03:35,364
things that matter, and savor the time you have.

45
00:03:35,364 --> 00:03:37,584
That's what you do when life is short.
